text=:Category: LinguisticDiscriminationInTheWild%0a:Essential: {Category.LinguisticDiscriminationInTheWild$:essential}%0a:Title: Discrimination Against Yorkshire Accents%0a:Author: solanaM%0a:Section: C%0a:Completed: 24.04.2021 - 07:44%0a:Status: complete%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradeitem:)%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradingcomment:)%0a%0a----%0a%0a%0a%25blue%25 '''Grading History'''%0a%0a[[#history]]%0a#foxbegin 210505-021803-165050#%0a* [-04.05.2021 - 19:18-] || TA_lili marked as complete%0a#foxend 210505-021803-165050#%0a[[#historyend]]%0a%0a%25blue%25 '''Comments for student'''%0a%0a[[#comments]]%0a%0a[[#commentsend]]%0a%0a----%0a----%0a!!%0a%0aSummary: \\%0a%0a[[#summary]]%0a%0aIn the UK, certain accents such as Yorkshire ones are discriminated against for not being as “proper” as Received Pronunciation (aka the Queen’s English).%0a%0a[[#summaryends]]%0a%0a----%0a[[#content]]%0a%0aIn this article, a young woman talks about discrimination she has faced for having a Yorkshire accent. When she moved to South England for school, where most of the elite universities are located, she experienced bullying due to her accent from her peers, as they though she sounded uneducated. She also explains that she has faced discrimination and judgement in job interviews for her accent, as employers expected her to have a more ‘posh’ accent based on her resume. One specific example she gives is that she says “ohrite” as a greeting rather than “alright.” This article then goes on to discuss other individual’s experiences with discrimination based on their Northern/Yorkshire accents, often being told they sound unintelligent or like low-class thieves.%0a	There are multiple aspects of Yorkshire accents that are considered ungrammatical when compared to Standard British English. H-dropping is common in this dialect in which [h] in words are deleted. Also, deletion of final stops and fricatives in words is not uncommon. There are also many instances of vowel substitution that is not consider correct grammar. For example [əʊ] is often replaced with the monophthong [ɔː] or [o:], and [ɛ] is sometimes replaced with [ə:]. Additionally, when a closed vowel comes before /l/, a schwa is inserted. These are just a few of the examples of the ‘ungrammatical’ structures associated with Yorkshire accents that led to accentism, especially in academic and professional settings.%0a%0aSources: https://www.vice.com/en/article/qjpdn7/accent-bias-job-discrimination-uk%0ahttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Yorkshire_dialect#Pronunciation%0a%0a%0a[[#contentends]]%0a----%0a(:GradedBy: TA_lili:)
