n words is not uncommon. There are also many instances of vowel substitution that is not consider correct grammar. For example [əʊ] is often replaced with the monophthong [ɔː] or [o:], and [ɛ] is sometimes replaced with [ə:]. Additionally, when a closed vowel comes before /l/, a schwa is inserted. These are just a few of the examples of the ‘ungrammatical’ structures associated with Yorkshire accents that led to accentism, especially in academic and professional settings.%0a%3c %0a%3c Sources: https://www.vice.com/en/article/qjpdn7/accent-bias-job-discrimination-uk%0a%3c https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Yorkshire_dialect#Pronunciation%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c [[#contentends]]%0a%3c ----%0a\ No newline at end of file%0a
